ProcedureHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: PROC BINNING DATA=CAS-libref.data-table < options > ;
    CODE FILE=filename ;
    FREQ variable ;
    INPUT variables < / option > ;
    OUTPUT OUT=CAS-libref.data-table < option > ;
    TARGET variable / EVENT=“category” ;

Binning is a common step in the data preparation stage of the model-building process. You can use binning
to classify missing variables, reduce the impact of outliers, and generate multiple effects. The generated
effects are useful and contain certain nonlinear information about the original interval variables.
The BINNING procedure supports a few binning methods that are described in the following subsections.
The BINNING procedure can also calculate the weight of evidence (WOE) and information value (IV) based
on binning results.

StatementHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: TARGET variable / EVENT=“category” ;

The TARGET statement names the variable that PROC BINNING uses to calculate the weight of evidence
and information value.
